ks"><div class=3D"text-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><h4>Calcu=
lating Percent Error</h4>
<p>In your everyday life, it's pretty common to make estimates of values ra=
ther than taking the time or brainpower to use exact ones. </p>

<p>If someone asks you how far the nearest gas station is, you'll probably =
say something like, "It's about <span class=3D"mjpage"><span class=3D"mjx-c=
html"><span class=3D"mjx-math" aria-label=3D"5\text{ miles}"><span class=3D=
"mjx-mrow" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"mjx-mn"><span class=3D"mjx-c=
har MJXc-TeX-main-R" style=3D"padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em=
;">5</span></span><span class=3D"mjx-mtext"><span class=3D"mjx-char MJXc-Te=
X-main-R" style=3D"padding-top: 0.372em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">&nbsp;mi=
les</span></span></span></span></span></span> away." That's an <em>estimate=
.</em> In most situations we come across, <em>estimated</em> or <em>approxi=
mate</em> values are all we need.</p>
</div><div class=3D"image-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><img s=
rc=3D"https://d20khd7ddkh5ls.cloudfront.net/percent_error_gasoline.jpg" alt=
=3D"Gas
"><div class=3D"image-content__caption"><p>Image by paulbr75 via <a href=3D=
"https://pixabay.com/photos/vintage-gas-pump-fuel-gasoline-gas-1600594/">Pi=
xabay</a> (<a href=3D"https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/dee=
d.en">CC0</a>)</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"text-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><=
p>However, there are instances where <strong>exact values</strong> are nece=
ssary. In some cases, it's important to know <em>how different your estimat=
ed and exact values are.</em> This is called <strong>percent error.</strong=
> This basically tells us how far off our estimate is from the actual value=
.</p>

<p>You will see this concept a lot when doing scientific experiments in ord=
er to calculate the error between the measured value and the theoretical va=
lue. </p>

<p>To calculate <strong>percent error</strong>, we'll use the formula below=
.</p>
</div><div class=3D"image-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><img s=
rc=3D"https://d20khd7ddkh5ls.cloudfront.net/percent_error_formula_2.jpg" al=
t=3D"% error =3D |Approximate value - Exact value|/Exact value * 100"><div =
class=3D"image-content__caption"><p>Image source: by Hannah Bonville</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"text-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><=
p>Recall that the straight lines around the numerator of the fraction repre=
sent <a href=3D"https://www.expii.com/t/absolute-value-definition-examples-=
9004#:~:text=3DAbsolute%20value%20is%20a%20number's,absolute%20value%20is%2=
0always%20positive."><strong>absolute value</strong></a>. That means that w=
hatever the difference between the approximate and exact values is, we will=
 take the <em>positive</em> version of it.</p>
</div><div class=3D"image-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><img s=
rc=3D"https://d20khd7ddkh5ls.cloudfront.net/chemistry_percent_error_example=
.jpg" alt=3D"In chemistry class, Inna estimates that a solid melts at 45 de=
grees Fahrenheit. She reads in her textbook later that the actual melting p=
oint for the solid is 47.6 degrees Fahrenheit.

What is the percent error of Inna's experiment?"><div class=3D"image-conten=
t__caption"><p>Image source: by Hannah Bonville</p>
</div></div><form class=3D"ask-content interactive-content-blocks__block"><=
